{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2c397f71-120e-4f49-bd04-8f9b7d2f5e4c","content":"Since you already have the dump file, you're past the collection stage. Here's how to analyze it:\n\n**Using `dotnet-dump analyze`** (cross-platform):\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\ndotnet-dump analyze your-file.dmp\n```\n\nUseful commands inside the analyzer:\n| Command | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `clrstack` | Managed call stack of current thread |\n| `clrthreads` | List all managed threads |\n| `pe` | Print last exception |\n| `dumpheap -stat` | Heap summary (for OOM issues) |\n| `setthread <id>` | Switch threads before running `clrstack` |\n\n**Typical workflow:**\n1. Run `pe` to check for an unhandled exception\n2. Run `clrthreads` to find faulting threads\n3. Use `setthread` + `clrstack` to inspect each\n\n**Alternatives:** You can also use **lldb** (Linux/macOS) with the SOS plugin, or **WinDbg** (Windows) for deeper native-level analysis.\n\nWould you like help running any of these commands on your dump file?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e2819a2c-c3e4-44ea-8c65-6918cc71971f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about analyzing a .dmp crash dump file. Let me check the available skills - there's a `dump-collect` skill, but its description says it's for configuring and collecting crash dumps, and explicitly states \"DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze.\"\n\nSo the skill is not appropriate here. I should help the user directly with guidance on analyzing their dump file.","outputTokens":398,"requestId":"7849:17168D:1F9539C:232624D:69FA9F71"},"id":"5ea26eb7-ce92-491b-941d-5fdca7b8cad1","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:55:08.465Z","parentId":"dd28db7f-e819-4e9f-86f7-befd412ecb1d"}
